comment.body:
You're right that `$('#modalNewsletter')` isn't always present in the document.

I checked it more closely and the inline trigger seems to be rendered only on the first visit, when the modal is actually shown. After a refresh/return visit, the server no longer includes that script, which is probably why you couldn't reproduce it.

In a private window, the initial page source contains:

```js 
$(window).on('load', function () {     
    $('#modalNewsletter').modal('show'); 
});
```

and the modal appears. After a refresh, both the script and the modal are gone.

Because of that, abort-current-inline-script still catches the popup on the only visit where it is triggered, without affecting the rest of the page.

I also tested abort-on-property-read. It blocks the modal too, but it breaks the lazy-loaded images in "Популярні дописи", "Рекомендовані дописи", and "Читайте також". Those sections rely on a jQuery-based lazyload (data-src / lazyload), and aborting reads of $ prevents it from initializing.

Would it be okay to keep abort-current-inline-script here?

